│ "new": "        // If the reduction is a boolean logic operation (or/and)   │
│ and the\n        // instruction is a compare, we must be careful about      │
│ poison safety.\n        // The original scalar code may have select         │
│ instructions that mask poison,\n        // but vectorizing the compares     │
│ directly can introduce poison where the\n        // original did not.       │
│ Disable vectorization of such compares by treating\n        // them as      │
│ reduced values.\n        // However, we must also consider that the compare │
│ may be used as a\n        // condition in a select that is a boolean logic  │
│ op (select with true/false).\n        // In that case, the compare is       │
│ already a boolean value and should be\n        // considered as a reduced   │
│ value, not as a reduction operation.\n        // The function isBoolLogicOp │
│ identifies such selects.\n        // If the compare is used by a select     │
│ that is a boolean logic op, we\n        // should treat it as a reduced     │
│ value.\n        if ((RdxKind == RecurKind::Or || RdxKind == RecurKind::And) │
│ &&\n            (isa<ICmpInst>(EdgeInst) || isa<FCmpInst>(EdgeInst))) {\n   │
│ // Check if any user of this compare is a select that is a boolean logic    │
